description.en: The Inspire Knowledge Graph contains (a) 102 food ingredients, (b) a 4-layer taxonomy of 150 ingredient categories, (c) sensory information for the ingredients (aromas, tastes, textures, trigeminals), (d) functional benefits of ingredients, (e) ingredient pairings.

definition.value: Represents the effects or advantages that a food ingredient or product provides beyond basic nutrition. These benefits may include specific health-promoting properties, culinary enhancements, or other functional attributes that contribute to overall well-being or enhance the overall quality of a food item.
Functional benefits related to antibacterial properties involve ingredients or products that help combat harmful bacteria.
Ingredients or products that can help regulate blood sugar levels.
Involve ingredients or products that aid in the breakdown and absorption of nutrients in the digestive tract.
Functional benefits for skin health involve ingredients or products that promote a healthy complexion and address skin-related issues.
Functional benefits for cardiovascular health support the heart and circulatory system, reducing the risk of heart-related conditions.
Ingredients or products that may assist in increasing body mass and muscle.
Ingredients or products that may promote better sleep quality and duration.
Functional benefits for weight-loss involve ingredients or products that may aid in achieving and maintaining a healthy weight.
Ingredients that provide a significant amount of calcium, vital for bone health.
Prebiotics are dietary fibers that nourish beneficial gut bacteria, supporting a healthy digestive system.
Functional benefits of aromatherapy involve the use of aromatic compounds from plants to promote relaxation, well-being, and mental clarity.
Functional benefits related to minerals focus on ingredients that provide essential minerals necessary for various bodily functions.
Ingredients or products with energy-related functional benefits provide a source of sustenance and vitality for the body.
Involve ingredients or products that support the development and maintenance of strong bones.
Probiotics are live microorganisms that provide health benefits when consumed, particularly in aiding digestion and supporting a healthy gut microbiome.
Ingredients or products with satiety-related functional benefits help promote feelings of fullness and satisfaction after eating.
Functional benefits related to aging focus on ingredients or products that may support healthy aging, including skin health and cognitive function.
Functional benefits related to vitamins involve ingredients that are rich in essential vitamins necessary for overall health.
Antioxidants help protect cells from damage caused by free radicals, which can contribute to aging and various diseases.
Involve ingredients or products that support healthy nerve function and transmission.
Functional benefits for muscle gain involve ingredients or products that support the development and maintenance of lean muscle mass.
Functional benefits for the brain are properties that support cognitive function, memory, and overall mental well-being.
Functional benefits for immunity involve ingredients or products that support the body's ability to defend against illnesses and infections.
Ingredients or products that may help reduce or manage stress levels in the body.
An idea or notion; a unit of thought.

definition.value: A sensory descriptor is a label used to describe a specific sensory property of an ingredient. We differentiate between 4 types: (a) Aroma descriptors contain properties like 'almond', 'cherry' and 'mustard'; (b) Texture descriptors contain properties like 'crunchy', 'hard' and 'gooey'; (c) Taste descriptors contain the five basic tastes 'salt', 'sour', 'sweet', 'bitter', and 'umami' and three additional descriptors 'fatty' (or 'oleogustus'), 'astringent', and 'pungent'; (d) Trigeminal taste descriptors contain taste sensations 'astringent', 'pungent', 'cooling' and 'tingling'.
An ingredient is an individual food entity or elaboration thereof (e.g. apple & apple jam).

scopeNote.value: A concept scheme may be defined to include concepts from different sources.

example.value: Thesauri, classification schemes, subject heading lists, taxonomies, 'folksonomies', and other types of controlled vocabulary are all examples of concept schemes. Concept schemes are also embedded in glossaries and terminologies.

definition.value: Aromas are the odorants or smells present in a food product. Aroma molecules are perceived through the mouth and the nose and are translated by our olfactory system. Aroma defines on average 80% of our flavor experience.
A pairing between two ingredients that share one or more key aroma molecules. The pairing has a key ingredient and a related ingredient.

Trigeminal taste (“other tastes”) are a set of tastes which are perceived as triggers sent to the brain via the trigeminal nerve, creating the conscious perception of touch-position and pain-temperature information. Trigeminal sensations are often associated with compounds found in certain foods; menthol for cooling is found in mint, spilanthol comes from a variety of plants, causing a tingling effect on the tongue (think wine and green tea) and capsaicin in chilies is what gives them their signature spiciness.

The aroma types represent the key odorants in the aroma profile of a customer product. There are 14 standard aroma types that can be found, e.g. fruity, floral, spicy, green, roasted, etc. Each of the aroma types are further defined by different aroma descriptors, e.g fruity-coconut or vegetable-potato.
Textures are the qualities of a food item that can be sensed through touch; i.e. the degree to which something is rough or smooth, or soft or hard.
A meaningful collection of concepts.

scopeNote.value: Labelled collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed under a 'node label' in the hierarchy.

definition.value: An ingredient category is a broad classification of related food components based on shared characteristics, used for organizing and understanding various ingredients in culinary and nutritional contexts.
Relates to confectionery products infused with herbs or spices, often creating unique flavor combinations.
Refers to a dairy product made by churning cream or milk, commonly used as a cooking fat or spread.
Refers to confectionery products with a high sugar content, including candies, gummies, and marshmallows.
Encompasses confectionery products made primarily from fruits, such as fruit jellies, fruit gummies, and fruit-filled chocolates.
Encompasses a wide variety of dairy products made from curdled milk, with different textures, flavors, and production methods.
Refers to the high-fat layer that forms on top of milk, often used in cooking, baking, or as a topping for desserts.
Encompasses confectionery products made primarily from chocolate, including chocolate bars, truffles, and pralines.
Includes confectionery products made with milk or milk-derived ingredients, such as fudge, caramels, and milk chocolates.
Includes various sauces used as condiments on the dining table, such as ketchup, mustard, and mayonnaise.
Refers to a sour-tasting liquid produced through the fermentation of ethanol, often used as a condiment or preservative.
Relates to cheeses with a semi-firm texture and flavors that range from mild to sharp, often suitable for slicing or grating.
Encompasses cheeses with a semi-soft or springy texture, offering a balance between firmness and creaminess.
Encompasses aged cheeses with a firm and dry texture, typically characterized by intense flavors and a long aging process.
Refers to cheeses that have been colored or aged with the addition of red cultures or bacteria, resulting in distinct flavors.
Refers to cheeses with a soft and spreadable texture, often creamy and mild in flavor.
Relates to the white liquid produced by mammals' mammary glands, often consumed as a beverage or used in various recipes.
Encompasses a type of cheese characterized by the presence of blue or green veins of mold, known for its distinct flavor.
Refers to soft, unripened cheeses with a high moisture content, often mild and creamy in flavor.
Includes dairy alternatives made from plant-based sources, such as almond milk, soy milk, or coconut milk.
Refers to a fermented dairy product made from milk, typically with added bacterial cultures, offering a creamy and tangy taste.
Refers to various edible creatures from the sea, including fish, shellfish (such as shrimp, lobster, or crab), and mollusks (such as clams, oysters, or mussels).
Refers to the flesh of animals used as food, such as beef, pork, lamb, or poultry, which can be cooked in various ways.
Encompasses protein-rich foods derived from plants, such as legumes, tofu, tempeh, seitan, and plant-based meat alternatives.
Refers to plant-based beverages made from nuts, such as almond milk or cashew milk, often used as a dairy milk substitute.
Encompasses distilled spirits made from sources other than grapes, such as whiskey, rum, vodka, and tequila.
Relates to distilled alcoholic beverages made specifically from agave plants, including mezcal and tequila.
Encompasses spreads made from ground nuts, such as peanut butter, almond butter, or hazelnut spread.
Includes alcoholic beverages produced by fermenting grapes or other fruits, offering a wide range of flavors, colors, and styles.
Refers to distilled spirits made from fermented grapes, such as brandy, cognac, and pisco.
Includes edible seeds enclosed in a hard shell, such as almonds, walnuts, cashews, and peanuts, often consumed as snacks or used in cooking.
Encompasses various edible aquatic creatures, often prepared as food, such as salmon, tuna, cod, or trout.
Includes edible insects consumed as food, such as crickets, mealworms, or grasshoppers, which are part of some cultural cuisines.
Includes small, edible plant embryos often used as ingredients in cooking, baking, or eaten as snacks, such as sesame seeds, chia seeds, and sunflower seeds.
Refers to a branch of cooking related to prepared meat products, such as cured meats, sausages, pâtés, and terrines.
Refers to beverages containing alcohol, including various types of beer, wine, spirits, and cocktails.
Includes beverages without alcohol, such as soft drinks, juices, water, coffee, tea, and non-alcoholic cocktails.
Encompasses distilled alcoholic beverages with a higher alcohol content, often flavored and consumed in small quantities.
Refers to a broad category of distilled alcoholic beverages, including liquors, whiskey, vodka, rum, gin, tequila, and others.
Encompasses a wide range of fermented alcoholic beverages made from grains, typically barley, flavored with hops and yeast.
Refers to a category of alcoholic beverages characterized by a bitter taste, often produced by botanical ingredients or hops.
Encompasses spices with a tangy or fruity flavor, such as tamarind, sumac, or dried berries, used to enhance sweet or savory dishes.
Includes blends of different spices and herbs, often used to season various dishes or add flavor to sauces, marinades, or rubs.
Encompasses beverages made from the leaves of the Camellia sinensis plant, offering various flavors and caffeine content.
Encompasses snack foods made from rice, such as rice cakes, rice crackers, or puffed rice snacks, often flavored or seasoned.
Includes spices derived from anise and licorice plants, offering distinctive flavors often used in culinary and confectionery preparations.
Includes crispy snack foods made from potatoes, corn, or other vegetables, often flavored and fried or baked.
Refers to a beverage made by steeping ingredients like herbs, fruits, or flowers in hot water, creating flavored and aromatic drinks.
Refers to a type of corn kernel that puffs up and becomes light and crispy when heated, commonly consumed as a snack.
Includes the extracted liquids from fruits or vegetables, often consumed as beverages or used as ingredients in recipes.
Includes spices with a nutty flavor profile, such as almonds, cashews, or hazelnuts, used to enhance the taste of dishes or desserts.
Refers to spices with a strong, sharp, or intense taste, often used to add heat or spiciness to foods, such as chili peppers or mustard seeds.
Refers to spices with a bitter taste, often used in small quantities to add complexity and depth of flavor to dishes.
Encompasses spices derived from citrus fruits, such as lemon zest, orange peel, or lime leaves, adding tangy and aromatic notes.
Refers to a distilled alcoholic beverage made from sugarcane byproducts, typically aged in oak barrels for flavor development.
Encompasses a neutral-tasting distilled spirit typically made from grains or potatoes, often used as a base for cocktails.
Includes distilled spirits flavored with juniper berries and other botanical ingredients, such as gin and jenever.
Refers to beverages containing stimulant ingredients like caffeine or taurine, often consumed to provide a temporary energy boost.
Encompasses waters infused with flavors, often derived from fruits, herbs, or botanical extracts, offering a refreshing taste.
Relates to distilled alcoholic beverages made from fermented grain mash, aged in wooden casks, and varying in flavor profiles.
Includes various coffee products, such as whole beans, ground coffee, instant coffee, and coffee-based beverages.
Relates to sweet dishes, cakes, pastries, and other treats typically consumed after a meal.
Encompasses vegetables that are botanically classified as fruits, such as tomatoes, cucumbers, eggplants, or bell peppers.
Refers to a wide range of beverages, including alcoholic and non-alcoholic drinks like juices, soft drinks, coffee, tea, and flavored waters.
Refers to grains and breakfast cereals such as oats, rice, pasta, and other grain-based products.
Refers to spices made from chili peppers, offering varying levels of heat and flavors, often used in spicy dishes or hot sauces.
Relates to sensory aspects and flavors associated with cigarettes.
Encompasses confectionery products made by heating sugar, often combined with butter, cream, or milk, resulting in a sweet and chewy treat.
Encompasses spices that create a warm and cozy flavor profile, often associated with fall or winter dishes, such as cloves, ginger, or allspice.
Encompasses small, edible fruits, often colorful and packed with antioxidants, such as strawberries, blueberries, and raspberries.
Refers to a group of fruits characterized by their acidic taste and high vitamin C content, including oranges, lemons, and grapefruits.
Includes spices derived from various pepper plants, such as black pepper, white pepper, or pink peppercorns, adding heat and pungency to dishes.
Includes various baked goods like bread, cookies, cakes, pastries, and viennoiserie.
Encompasses sweet treats like chocolate confections, milk confections, sugar confections, and fruit confections.
Encompasses vegetables with edible bulbs, such as onions, garlic, shallots, or fennel, used as aromatic ingredients in cooking.
Refers to vegetables where the flowers or flower buds are consumed, such as broccoli, cauliflower, artichokes, or capers.
Involves dairy products like butter, cheese, cream, milk, plant-based dairy alternatives, and yogurt.
Refers to a sweet, viscous liquid produced by bees from flower nectar, often used as a natural sweetener and flavoring agent.
Encompasses products made from or containing chocolate, including confections and desserts.
Includes various sauces, dips, spreads, and pickled products used to enhance the flavor of food.
Includes thick, sweet liquids made by dissolving sugar in water or other liquids, often used as sweeteners or flavorings in beverages or desserts.
Relates to the sensory perception resulting from the combination of taste and aroma in food and beverages.
Refers to macronutrients that are a concentrated source of energy, such as butter, lard, and oils, used in cooking and baking.
Refers to non-alcoholic carbonated beverages, commonly known as sodas or pop, with a wide range of flavors and sweetness levels.
Encompasses chilled tea-based beverages, often served with ice, and may be sweetened or flavored with fruits or herbs.
Refers to substances used to add or enhance color in food and beverages, such as natural or synthetic food dyes.
Relates to the distinct taste or aroma of a food or beverage, often achieved through natural or artificial flavorings.
Refers to spices with a sweet taste or aroma, such as cinnamon, vanilla, or nutmeg, often used in desserts, baked goods, or sweet beverages.
Includes various liquid fats derived from plants or animals, often used for cooking, frying, and as dressings or flavorings.
Encompasses substances added to food products to enhance taste, texture, appearance, or extend shelf life, such as preservatives or emulsifiers.
Refers to protein-rich foods such as meat, fish, seafood, plant-based proteins, and insect-based products.
Relates to edible flowers used in cooking, garnishing, or flavoring food and beverages.
Encompasses vegetables where the seeds or seed pods are the primary edible part, such as beans, peas, or corn.
Refers to young, tender shoots or germinated seeds of various vegetables, often used as a fresh ingredient in salads or sandwiches.
Refers to a diverse range of fruits, including citrus fruits, berries, tropical fruits, and other fruit varieties.
Encompasses various fats and oils used in cooking and food preparation.
Refers to vegetables where the root portion is consumed, such as carrots, potatoes, turnips, or radishes, often used in soups or stews.
Includes substances added to food for various purposes like flavoring, coloring, preservation, and texture enhancement.
Includes vegetables and algae that grow in the sea or saltwater environments, such as seaweed, kelp, or sea asparagus.
Refers to spicy peppers, often used as a seasoning or ingredient to add heat and flavor to dishes.
Includes various types of nuts and seeds used as ingredients or snacks.
Relates to sensory aspects not covered by other specific categories
Includes a variety of edible leafy vegetables, such as spinach, lettuce, kale, or Swiss chard, often used in salads or cooked as side dishes.
Encompasses culinary and medicinal herbs used for flavoring, garnishing, or as natural remedies.
Includes vegetables where the stem or stalk portion is consumed, such as asparagus, celery, or rhubarb.
Refers to vegetables where the enlarged underground stem or tuber is consumed, such as potatoes, yams, or taro.
Relates to items or substances not intended for human consumption, such as non-edible products or materials.
Refers to a diverse group of fruits grown in tropical regions, often exotic in appearance and flavors, such as mangoes, pineapples, and papayas.
Encompasses herbs used primarily for cooking and flavoring dishes, such as basil, thyme, rosemary, and parsley.
Relates to fruits with a central core containing seeds, often sweet and juicy, such as apples, pears, and quinces.
Includes fruits with a single hard seed or pit surrounded by juicy flesh, such as peaches, plums, cherries, and apricots.
Encompasses products consumed to supplement the diet and provide additional nutrients, vitamins, or minerals.
Includes vegetables where the leaves are the primary edible part, such as cabbage, Swiss chard, or bok choy.
Pertains to liquids used in electronic cigarettes or vaping devices for inhalation.
Encompasses various edible fungi, including mushrooms, truffles, and other types of fungi used in culinary preparations.
Refers to highly concentrated liquids extracted from plants, often used for their scent, flavor, or potential therapeutic properties.
Refers to herbs used for their potential health benefits or medicinal properties, such as chamomile, echinacea, and ginseng.
Relates to substances or compounds used for medical purposes, including over-the-counter drugs or prescription medications.
Encompasses fruits with a hard, outer rind and soft inner flesh, such as melons, cucumbers, and squash.
Includes sweetening agents like sugars, syrups, and artificial sweeteners used to enhance the sweetness of food and drinks.
Fragrances are aromatic substances (perfums, compounds,...) that are used to add pleasant odors to people, objects, or spaces
Personal care refers to products that individuals engage in to maintain their personal hygiene, appearance, and overall well-being. Includes hygiene, skin care, hair care, oral care and cosmetics
Refers to a wide range of edible vegetables, including bulb vegetables, leafy greens, root vegetables, and sea-grown vegetables.

Broths and stocks are flavorful liquids used as a base for soups, sauces, and various dishes. They are created by simmering ingredients like meats, bones, vegetables, and seasonings in water to extract their flavors.
Pertains to moist powder tobacco products, usually placed under the lip for extended periods.
Encompasses various spices and spice blends used to add flavor and aroma to dishes.

A dish refers to a prepared and cooked food item that is intended to be consumed as a single serving. It can consist of one or more ingredients that have been combined and cooked together to create a specific flavor, texture, and presentation.
Refers to crispy or puffed snack foods made from corn; often flavored or seasoned.
Relates to a category of baked goods made with dough or pastry dough, often used for pies, tarts, and pastries.
Refers to a type of pastry made from a yeast-leavened dough, including croissants, pain au chocolat, and Danish pastries.
Type of spicy table sauce made from chili peppers or chili pepper extracts.
Bread is a staple food made from a combination of flour and water, along with other ingredients such as yeast, salt, and sometimes sweeteners or fats. The dough is typically baked.
Refers to baked products made primarily from flour, water, and yeast or other leavening agents.
Refers to a specific type of beverage designed to replenish fluids, electrolytes, and provide carbohydrates during or after intense physical activity.
Encompasses different types of sauces used for flavoring and enhancing the taste of dishes.
Refers to various types of photosynthetic organisms that grow in water, such as seaweed or microalgae, which can be consumed as food or used as ingredients.
Includes a wide range of snack foods like chips, crisps, popcorn, and rice snacks.
Includes edible vegetables that grow in the sea or saltwater environments, such as seaweed, kelp, or sea asparagus, often used in Asian cuisines.
Encompasses different types of lettuce, such as romaine, iceberg, or butterhead, often used in salads or as a bed for other ingredients.
Relates to oats, a type of cereal grain commonly used in breakfast cereals, porridge, and baked goods.
Includes savory preparations used for dipping or spreading on other foods, such as hummus, guacamole, and cheese spreads.
Refers to the edible seeds of the rice plant, often consumed as a staple food in many cultures.
Encompasses various types of noodles and pasta products made from wheat flour, water, and sometimes eggs.
Relates to condiments made from fruits, vegetables, or herbs, typically used to add flavor and enhance dishes.
Refers to sweet spreads made from fruit or fruit juice, typically preserved with sugar and pectin.
Encompasses preserved vegetables or fruits, often soaked in a brine or vinegar solution to impart a tangy flavor.
Encompasses processed cereal-based products typically consumed as breakfast, including flakes, granola, and oatmeal.
Refers to various cereal grains used as staple foods, including wheat, rice, corn, oats, barley, and others.
Refers to sweet-tasting, soluble carbohydrates added to foods and beverages to provide sweetness, flavor and energy. Includes natural and synthetic sugars.

Cookies are small, sweet, baked treats, typically made from a mixture of flour, sugar, butter, and other ingredients. Cookies come in a wide variety of flavors, shapes, and textures, and are enjoyed as a snack.
Encompasses sweet baked goods like cookies and cakes, typically made from a combination of flour, sugar, eggs, and flavorings.

Taste is the perception produced or stimulated when a substance in the mouth reacts chemically with taste receptor cells located on taste buds in the oral cavity, mostly on the tongue. Taste, along with olfaction and trigeminal nerve stimulation (registering texture, pain, and temperature), determines flavors of food and other substances. A taste is how the taste buds experience the 5 taste types - sweet, sour, bitter, salty and umami. Additional descriptors pungent, astringent and fatty also apply. A food is usually a blend of tastes, each in different concentrations.
Specifies the key ingredient in an ingredient pairing.

Establishes a relationship between an individual ingredient and its corresponding ingredient category. This property serves to categorize and organize ingredients based on their shared attributes, facilitating structured representation and classification within the domain of food knowledge.
Links a concept to a concept related by meaning.

scopeNote.value: This property should not be used directly, but as a super-property for all properties denoting a relationship of meaning between concepts.

definition.value: Associates an ingredient to a texture.
skos:broadMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.
Relates a concept to a concept that is more specific in meaning.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

comment.en: Narrower concepts are typically rendered as children in a concept hierarchy (tree).

definition.value: skos:broaderTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:broader.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:broaderTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

definition.value: Expresses how strongly a certain aroma is perceived by a person, based on Foodpairing benchmarking.
Relates a concept to a concept that is more general in meaning.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

comment.en: Broader concepts are typically rendered as parents in a concept hierarchy (tree).

definition.value: Relates a concept to a concept with which there is an associative semantic relationship.
Specifies the aroma type of the sensory descriptor.
Specifies the related ingredient in an ingredient pairing.
A notation, also known as classification code, is a string of characters such as "T58.5" or "303.4833" used to uniquely identify a concept within the scope of a given concept scheme.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:notation is used with a typed literal in the object position of the triple.

definition.value: Represents the 'raw' sensory value for certain descriptors.
Relates two concepts coming, by convention, from different schemes, and that have comparable meanings

comment.en: These concept mapping relations mirror semantic relations, and the data model defined below is similar (with the exception of skos:exactMatch) to the data model defined for semantic relations. A distinct vocabulary is provided for concept mapping relations, to provide a convenient way to differentiate links within a concept scheme from links between concept schemes. However, this pattern of usage is not a formal requirement of the SKOS data model, and relies on informal definitions of best practice.

definition.value: Relates a resource (for example a concept) to a concept scheme in which it is included.

scopeNote.value: A concept may be a member of more than one concept scheme.

definition.value: skos:closeMatch is used to link two concepts that are sufficiently similar that they can be used interchangeably in some information retrieval applications. In order to avoid the possibility of "compound errors" when combining mappings across more than two concept schemes, skos:closeMatch is not declared to be a transitive property.
Associates an ingredient to an aroma.
Relates, by convention, a concept scheme to a concept which is topmost in the broader/narrower concept hierarchies for that scheme, providing an entry point to these hierarchies.
skos:relatedMatch is used to state an associative mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.
Associates a flavour to an ingredient. This property is never used; instead, its subproperties are used.
Relates a concept to the concept scheme that it is a top level concept of.
Associates an ingredient to a trigeminal taste.
Establishes a relationship between a food ingredient and a specific functional benefit.
Associates a flavour (aroma, taste, texture, trigeminal) to a sensory descriptor.

skos:exactMatch is used to link two concepts, indicating a high degree of confidence that the concepts can be used interchangeably across a wide range of information retrieval applications. skos:exactMatch is a transitive property, and is a sub-property of skos:closeMatch.

comment.en: skos:exactMatch is disjoint with each of the properties skos:broadMatch and skos:relatedMatch.

definition.value: skos:narrowMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.
Associates an ingredient to a taste.
skos:narrowerTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:narrower.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:narrowerTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

definition.value: Relates an ordered collection to the RDF list containing its members.

comment.en:
For any resource, every item in the list given as the value of the
      skos:memberList property is also a value of the skos:member property.

definition.value: Associates an ingredient pairing with one or more ingredients.

A metric measuring how well two ingredients match together in an ingredient pairing. It corresponds to the relative matching score of one ingredient with another and is dependent on the highest absolute matching score of a specific ingredient. The absolute matching score is transformed into a percentage relative to the highest absolute score for that specific product. The matching score in the Foodpairing® Flavor Database is a relative matching score. The best matching ingredient of the Foodpairing® Flavor Database for a customer product has a 100% match. The matching score of the other ingredients is relative to the aroma score of the best matching ingredient.
Relates a collection to one of its members.
